      "input_text": "Research the history of construction of Hagia Sophia",
      "output_text": "Here is a detailed summary of the history of the construction of Hagia Sophia (Holy Wisdom) in Constantinople (modern-day Istanbul).\n\n### A Detailed History of the Construction of Hagia Sophia\n\nThe Hagia Sophia we see today is not the first church built on that site. Its history is a story of two failed predecessors and one monumental, world-changing construction project. The building's construction can be divided into three distinct phases: the First, Second, and Third (and current) Church.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 1: The First Church (The Magna Ecclesia) \u2013 c. 360-404 AD\n\n- **Patron:** Emperor Constantius II (son of Constantine the Great). While Constantine I had chosen the site for a major church, it was his son who dedicated the first structure.\n- **Construction:** Built as a traditional, timber-roofed basilica with a nave, aisles, and an atrium. It was inaugurated in 360 AD.\n- **Name:** Originally called the **Magna Ecclesia** (Great Church), it was only later referred to as Hagia Sophia (Holy Wisdom).\n- **Fate:** The first church was a center of religious and political turmoil. It was the site of the exile of St. John Chrysostom, the Archbishop of Constantinople. This event sparked a m",
